r_disclosure_disabled":false,"disclosed_at":"2019-07-09T13:43:59.828Z","bug_reporter_agreed_on_going_public_at":"2019-07-03T11:18:36.939Z","team_member_agreed_on_going_public_at":"2019-07-09T13:43:59.720Z","comments_closed?":false,"facebook_team?":false,"team_private?":false,"vulnerability_information":"Hello Weblate Team!\n\nI found HTML injection and information disclosure in support panel\n\n###Description\nThere is a form to ```weblate.org``` and ```hosted.weblate.org``` to send to support\nI poisoned the request, where I inserted such payload in all fields:\n```\n\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"[SERVER]\"\u003e\n```\n\nAfter that, when my payload got into the support panel, it was reproduced and the picture was uploaded, after that requests were sent to my server\n\n#####So HTML injection is there\nFurther, having examined in detail the requests that came to me on the server, I saw (private) ip addresses of administrators or employees (support panel)\n\n###### IP Adresses\n```\n37.9.65.65\n89.187.189.240\n95.108.197.9\n178.154.167.78\n```\n\n###### User Agent\n```\nUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (iPad; CPU OS 12_3_1 like Mac OS X) AppleWebKit/605.1.15 (KHTML, like Gecko) Canary\n```\n\n## Impact\n\nThe vulnerability allows you to execute HTML code in the support panel, also steal personal data of administrators, employees, for example: IP Addresses, which browsers employees use, and so on.\n\n\nBest regards Bogdan","weakness":{"id":18,"name":"Information Disclosure"},"original_report_id":null,"original_report_url":null,"attachments":[{"id":521325,"file_name":"_________________2019-07-03_11-14-51.png","expiring_url":"https://hackerone-us-west-2-production-attachments.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/000/521/325/ecd450218828205bb2d28c181b278442d3835348/_________________2019-07-03_11-14-51.png?response-content-disposition=attachment%3B%20filename%3D%22_________________2019-07-03_11-14-51.png%22%3B%20filename%2A%3DUTF-8%27%27_________________2019-07-03_11-14-51.png\u0026response-conten